  "text": "Let us now consider that the binary quantizer introduces a white uniform noise. This is a standard approximation in the analysis of -modulators. Then, the characteristic equation of the oscillator is [CITATION_1] By adjusting the value of to , it is possible to force an oscillation in the circuit. However, in our case, it is clear that this is not a necessary condition. The bit stream at the output of the binary quantizer remains constant as a function of the force delta area , which only acts as a scaling factor of the position waveform of the MEMS device, and, thus, does not change the output of the quantizer. It will be shown later in Section II, however, that the sign of must be the sign of in order to have a sustained oscillation. The resulting oscillation frequency is , where , called the normalized digital oscillation frequency, is given by the following expression [CITATION_2] : (9) Equation (9) implies that the oscillation frequency is a function of the sampling frequency, the mechanical resonator, and its damping losses. It is interesting to see that, for a system with no damping losses and , the oscillation frequency is equal to the natural frequency of the mechanical resonator . This is observed in Fig. 2 , where plots of as a function of the sampling ratio for three different damping values are shown. It is also observed that a loss of linearity between and appears and becomes more evident for increasing values of the damping loss factor.",
